<h2 id="materials">Materials</h2>

<p>Many resistors uses carbon as a main material to provide indicated value of resistance. Carbon is a semiconductive material that conductivity can be controlled with mixture with other materials. In early 20th centry resistor was made with carbon and ceramic and resin (maybe still the case too?). I had a wood charcoal from a firepit that I crushed up mixed with acuired powered charcoal for carbon, and clay harvested from Eastern Shore Maryland. I needed them like a bread. I have put the mixture on to two copper wires that are couple milimeter apart. After it was dry, I have checked the resistance. Number of them ranged from 80K ohm to 600K ohm. Some iteration with too little carbon did not conduct at all.</p>

